## bayesian_diagnosticity  — posterior 0.000, ELPD-LOO -746.07

Random-looking sequences are diagnostic of a fair coin over salient non-random alternatives: alternating, biased, and streaky generators.

## raw_alternation_count  — posterior 0.000, ELPD-LOO -1664.59

People perceive sequences with a higher raw count of alternations as more random, regardless of sequence length.

## high_alternation_rate  — posterior 0.000, ELPD-LOO -1664.57

People judge sequence randomness based on the proportion of alternations, perceiving sequences with a higher alternation rate as strictly more random.

## ideal_alternation_rate  — posterior 0.000, ELPD-LOO -815.47

People judge sequence randomness by comparing the proportion of alternating outcomes to a subjective ideal alternation rate, perceiving sequences closer to this ideal as more random.

## inner_loop_model  — posterior 0.681, ELPD-LOO -629.24

People judge sequence randomness based purely on outcome frequencies, paradoxically perceiving sequences with a greater imbalance between the number of heads and tails as more random.

## imbalance_with_lapse  — posterior 0.319, ELPD-LOO -629.99

People judge sequence randomness based purely on outcome frequencies, perceiving sequences with a greater proportion imbalance as more random, but their judgments are moderated by a constant lapse rate representing random guessing.

## quadratic_imbalance  — posterior 0.000, ELPD-LOO -669.96

People judge sequence randomness based on outcome frequencies, with perceived randomness growing quadratically as the proportion of heads and tails deviates further from a balanced distribution.

## iter0_candidate0  — posterior 0.000, ELPD-LOO -732.32

People judge sequence randomness based on outcome frequencies, perceiving sequences with a larger absolute difference between the raw count of heads and tails as more random.

## iter0_candidate2  — posterior 0.000, ELPD-LOO -712.46

People judge sequence randomness based purely on the relative length of the longest streak of identical outcomes, perceiving sequences with a larger normalized maximum run as less random.
